@matto__matto exactly. to me there's nothing wrong with using premade assets, especially if it's an effort to keep prices low, but only if it's transparent. passing them off as original art and charging 3 eth would be deception

hard to think of a game application for nfts that requires charging anything more than next to nothing, especially if you believe in the scale you're capable of

just to wrap this up and be clear: taking 3 eth for these is not okay and i side completely with the buyers, who should be refunded. if the project's creator is acting in good faith they need to demonstrate it now. fudging the line between art and game asset is bad enough

@0xmts could be. i think intent matters a lot and it's honestly hard for me to read. either way if i were a buyer i'd be pissed, i'm certainly not excusing the poor execution for 3 eth. this was bound to go poorly
@MeCryptoCookie this

@ElfoCrypto you really rugged me with this reply

don't get me wrong, i'm not defending this; if pixelmon were promising original characters and they just bought the assets, then that's a scam. and of course buyers want their game characters to look good on opensea if that's the only thing you can do with them right now
were the buyers expecting art, or were they expecting an arrangement of voxels that can be rendered in an infinite number of ways and whose primary value is their interactivity within a game space?

what i'm seeing is incredibly poor execution, not a rug pull. i'm also seeing nft-based games being held to the standard of art, which they frankly shouldn't. lots of games use unity assets (seems like these were licensed properly, or that was the intent)
